1
00:00:19,302 --> 00:00:21,302
[GARBLED NOISES]

2
00:00:23,106 --> 00:00:25,106
[CHATTERING]

3
00:00:30,413 --> 00:00:32,413
MAN:
What are you doing?

4
00:00:34,317 --> 00:00:37,143
Get back in the fucking vehicle, Mike!

5
00:00:37,153 --> 00:00:39,153
[PANTING]

6
00:00:39,222 --> 00:00:42,988
Mike, get back in the fucking vehicle.

7
00:00:43,660 --> 00:00:46,151
[STATIC CRACKLES]

8
00:00:46,963 --> 00:00:50,262
Let's go, Mike, now!

9
00:00:59,142 --> 00:01:01,142
MIKE:
Dad?

10
00:01:03,513 --> 00:01:05,004
Daddy?

11
00:01:05,014 --> 00:01:07,107
I can hardly hear you.

12
00:01:07,450 --> 00:01:11,445
MAN [OVER PHONE]:
I said your son has gone AWOL.

13
00:01:12,088 --> 00:01:14,088
HANK:
My son's in Iraq.

14
00:01:14,124 --> 00:01:18,184
Your son was in Iraq, sir.
His unit arrived stateside four days ago.

15
00:01:18,194 --> 00:01:21,221
Soldier, if my son were back,
I'd sure as hell know it.

16
00:01:21,231 --> 00:01:24,991
He has until Sunday to get back
or he'll be listed as absent.

17
00:01:25,001 --> 00:01:27,636
I'm sorry, I have another call.

18
00:01:32,375 --> 00:01:33,666
[BEEPS]

19
00:01:33,676 --> 00:01:37,671
FEMALE VOICE [ON MACHINE]:
You have no messages.

20
00:01:41,151 --> 00:01:43,151
[COMPUTER CHIMES]

21
00:01:59,035 --> 00:02:01,731
[PHONE RINGS THEN CLICKS]

22
00:02:01,905 --> 00:02:05,431
MIKE: Hey, this is Mike. Leave a message.
If I ever get a signal, I'll call you back.

23
00:02:05,441 --> 00:02:06,699
[PHONE BEEPS]

24
00:02:06,709 --> 00:02:13,509
Mike, it's your old man. Heard you're back.
Give me a call when you get a chance.

25
00:02:19,255 --> 00:02:22,282
PRESIDENT BUSH [ON RADIO]:
Think about that. Freedom is on the march...

26
00:02:22,292 --> 00:02:25,018
...and we're safer because of it.

27
00:02:25,028 --> 00:02:27,223
Iraq is still dangerous.

28
00:02:27,397 --> 00:02:32,158
It is dangerous because that society
is becoming more free...

29
00:02:32,168 --> 00:02:34,060
...and heading toward democracy.

30
00:02:34,070 --> 00:02:37,063
REPORTER [ON TV]:
Analysts say a broader strategy is at work...

31
00:02:37,073 --> 00:02:41,100
...one that began with the offensive
in the Sunni Triangle city of Samarra...

32
00:02:41,110 --> 00:02:43,002
...earlier this month.

33
00:02:43,012 --> 00:02:45,817
[MAN SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY ON TV]

34
00:02:45,982 --> 00:02:47,982
There you go.

35
00:02:49,519 --> 00:02:51,377
You sure that thing's gonna fit?

36
00:02:51,387 --> 00:02:54,702
You gotta trust somebody
sometime, Hank.

37
00:03:07,070 --> 00:03:09,368
-Anyone call?
-Nope.

38
00:03:12,075 --> 00:03:14,100
[PHONE RINGING]

39
00:03:17,914 --> 00:03:20,340
WOMAN [OVER PHONE]:
Fort Rudd, how may I direct your call?

40
00:03:20,350 --> 00:03:24,744
First Sergeant Arnold Bickman,
Criminal Investigations Division.

41
00:03:24,754 --> 00:03:28,548
I'm sorry, sir. I have no one
by that name on base.

42
00:03:28,558 --> 00:03:30,558
Thank you.

43
00:03:32,896 --> 00:03:34,896
[SIGHS]

44
00:03:36,799 --> 00:03:39,094
Anything you wanna tell me?

45
00:03:54,984 --> 00:03:56,876
JOAN:
Why can't I go with you?

46
00:03:56,886 --> 00:03:58,578
If he's someplace celebrating...

47
00:03:58,588 --> 00:04:01,481
...last thing he needs is his mother
walking in on him.

48
00:04:01,491 --> 00:04:05,518
-I'll call you when I get there tomorrow.
-It's a two-day drive.

49
00:04:05,528 --> 00:04:07,528
For some people.

50
00:04:44,968 --> 00:04:47,026
You don't wanna let it touch the ground.

51
00:04:47,036 --> 00:04:49,036
Okay.

52
00:04:50,573 --> 00:04:53,201
-Where you from?
-El Salvador.

53
00:04:54,143 --> 00:04:57,704
Do you know what it means
when a flag flies upside down?

54
00:04:57,714 --> 00:05:00,873
-No.
-It's an international distress signal.

55
00:05:00,883 --> 00:05:02,883
-No shit?
-No shit.

56
00:05:03,152 --> 00:05:06,045
It means we're in a lot of trouble,
so come save our ass...

57
00:05:06,055 --> 00:05:09,115
...because we don't have a prayer in hell
of saving ourselves.

58
00:05:09,125 --> 00:05:11,590
-It says a lot.
-Yes, it does.

59
00:05:11,661 --> 00:05:13,152
You know how to do it now?

60
00:05:13,162 --> 00:05:15,426
-Oh, yes.
-Good.

61
00:05:21,671 --> 00:05:24,731
MAN [ON RADIO]:
This whole concept of "Vote or Die!"...

62
00:05:24,741 --> 00:05:26,632
...to me the question is:

63
00:05:26,642 --> 00:05:28,167
Are they gonna vote?

64
00:05:28,177 --> 00:05:32,572
Are they gonna leave the bong
long enough to actually vote?

65
00:05:32,582 --> 00:05:34,582
I don't know.

66
00:05:42,258 --> 00:05:44,183
MIKE [IN VOICEOVER]:
Dad?

67
00:05:44,193 --> 00:05:45,551
[STATIC CRACKLES]

68
00:05:45,561 --> 00:05:47,520
Daddy?

69
00:05:47,530 --> 00:05:49,530
BOY:
Dad?

70
00:06:03,613 --> 00:06:05,638
Dad?

71
00:06:11,187 --> 00:06:13,187
Dad?

72
00:06:52,328 --> 00:06:54,320
MAN [ON RADIO]:
A strong low-pressure system...

73
00:06:54,330 --> 00:06:56,489
...will pass southward
across New Mexico tonight...

74
00:06:56,499 --> 00:06:59,992
...bringing with it colder temperatures
and overcast skies.

75
00:07:00,002 --> 00:07:02,297
SOLDIER:
Go ahead, sergeant.

76
00:07:04,774 --> 00:07:06,899
SOLDIER:
Thank you, ma'am.

77
00:07:12,648 --> 00:07:14,648
Sergeant Deerfield?

78
00:07:17,453 --> 00:07:19,445
-Hi.
-Thanks. I know you're busy.

79
00:07:19,455 --> 00:07:23,082
I wish you told me you were coming.
I could've made a little more time.

80
00:07:23,092 --> 00:07:25,318
Bet the base has changed a lot
since your day.

81
00:07:25,328 --> 00:07:26,919
-Thanks, corporal.
CORPORAL: Welcome.

82
00:07:26,929 --> 00:07:28,354
What about his buddies?

83
00:07:28,364 --> 00:07:30,364
We asked, of course.

84
00:07:30,967 --> 00:07:33,793
The rest of my guys
just got back from a 72.

85
00:07:33,803 --> 00:07:36,129
I don't wanna seem like
I'm not concerned.

86
00:07:36,139 --> 00:07:39,832
Where they been, it's a miracle
more guys don't blow off for a few days.

87
00:07:39,842 --> 00:07:43,752
Would you mind if I had a look
at his quarters?

88
00:07:43,880 --> 00:07:45,880
No.

89
00:07:51,087 --> 00:07:53,453
-Penning.
-Yes, sarge.

90
00:07:53,623 --> 00:07:56,616
-This is Specialist Deerfield's father.
-Good to meet you.

91
00:07:56,626 --> 00:07:58,217
-Have you heard from Mike?
-No.

92
00:07:58,227 --> 00:08:00,219
He wants to look at his son's quarters.

93
00:08:00,229 --> 00:08:03,156
Certainly, sir. Shortcut's through here.

94
00:08:03,166 --> 00:08:05,391
Me and Mike go back to Bosnia.

95
00:08:05,401 --> 00:08:08,971
He's sure told me
enough stories about you.

96
00:08:09,772 --> 00:08:12,932
-He hasn't called or anything?
-Does that surprise you?

97
00:08:12,942 --> 00:08:16,335
You know better than me,
but I recall Mike showing up for roll call...

98
00:08:16,345 --> 00:08:18,638
...with a collarbone
sticking through his skin.

99
00:08:18,648 --> 00:08:21,845
Long, Ortiez. This is Doc's dad.

100
00:08:22,018 --> 00:08:25,845
-Oh, honored to meet you, sir.
-Good to meet you.

101
00:08:25,855 --> 00:08:27,046
Doc?

102
00:08:27,056 --> 00:08:29,749
A nickname we gave him.
Made no sense.

103
00:08:29,759 --> 00:08:31,886
That's Mike's room there.

104
00:08:32,061 --> 00:08:34,287
You boys have any idea
where Mike could be?

105
00:08:34,297 --> 00:08:35,955
-No, sir.
-Sorry.

106
00:08:35,965 --> 00:08:38,591
-Must be one hell of a woman.
-Hmm, yeah.

107
00:08:38,601 --> 00:08:40,293
Good to meet you, sir.

108
00:08:40,303 --> 00:08:46,168
When you hear from Mike, you tell him
to get his butt back here, okay?

109
00:08:50,446 --> 00:08:52,446
Sergeant?

110
00:08:52,715 --> 00:08:55,942
This is Specialist Deerfield's dad.
We've come to look at his bunk.

111
00:08:55,952 --> 00:09:00,542
Roger. I thought you were
someone trying to steal shit.

112
00:09:01,591 --> 00:09:03,216
Is that your room?

113
00:09:03,226 --> 00:09:05,861
Yeah. That's Mike's bunk there.

114
00:09:08,998 --> 00:09:11,463
It was nice to meet you, sir.

115
00:09:14,070 --> 00:09:16,070
Who's that?

116
00:09:16,239 --> 00:09:18,239
We lost a man.

117
00:09:31,220 --> 00:09:33,220
[HANK CHUCKLES]

118
00:09:33,322 --> 00:09:34,747
That's your duffel, right?

119
00:09:34,757 --> 00:09:36,349
Yep.

120
00:09:36,359 --> 00:09:40,419
Tried to convince him to take the one
he was issued. It's like talking to a wall.

121
00:09:40,429 --> 00:09:42,429
[HANK CHUCKLES]

122
00:09:55,011 --> 00:09:56,535
No photographs.

123
00:09:56,545 --> 00:09:58,070
Sorry?

124
00:09:58,080 --> 00:10:00,906
Mike's always taking pictures
and e-mailing them to me...

125
00:10:00,916 --> 00:10:03,409
...and I don't see any photographs...

126
00:10:03,419 --> 00:10:05,419
...or a camera.

127
00:10:05,888 --> 00:10:09,458
CARNELLI:
Property theft is a real problem.

128
00:10:10,326 --> 00:10:14,321
-Guess it was the same during your stint.
-Yeah.

129
00:10:15,364 --> 00:10:20,559
You mind if I take this? His mother
gave it to him and I left mine at home.

130
00:10:20,569 --> 00:10:24,649
I'd like to, but I can't
let you remove anything.

131
00:10:24,740 --> 00:10:26,736
I understand.

132
00:10:26,746 --> 00:10:28,742
Okay.

133
00:10:31,681 --> 00:10:33,806
MAN [ON TV]: I think New Mexico
is a very important state...

134
00:10:33,816 --> 00:10:35,241
...and I want to win New Mexico.

135
00:10:35,251 --> 00:10:39,378
I think New Mexico has great
possibilities of better jobs...

136
00:10:39,388 --> 00:10:42,873
...more jobs.
You've got those wonderful--

137
00:10:43,426 --> 00:10:46,319
MAN: This phone's been around
some intense heat.

138
00:10:46,329 --> 00:10:50,239
HANK: It's been in Iraq.
MAN: That could do it.

139
00:10:51,233 --> 00:10:53,233
All right.

140
00:10:55,805 --> 00:10:58,185
Oh, this is seriously fried.

141
00:10:59,208 --> 00:11:02,769
Let's see. Okay.

142
00:11:02,945 --> 00:11:04,737
Address book.

143
00:11:04,747 --> 00:11:08,307
All right, there's numbers for barracks,
burgers, chicken, Mom...

144
00:11:08,317 --> 00:11:10,615
...pizza, TD's, Ted.

145
00:11:10,786 --> 00:11:12,078
What's TD's?

146
00:11:12,088 --> 00:11:15,681
That's a local joint. Could've been more,
but that's all that's left.

147
00:11:15,691 --> 00:11:18,918
-Okay, thanks. How much?
-You want the media?

148
00:11:18,928 --> 00:11:20,186
[SNIFFS]

149
00:11:20,196 --> 00:11:21,754
Media?

150
00:11:21,764 --> 00:11:23,764
Yeah. Look.

151
00:11:28,938 --> 00:11:31,297
BONNER [ON MONITOR]
Speed up!

152
00:11:31,307 --> 00:11:33,571
GABRIEL:
No. This is trash.

153
00:11:35,311 --> 00:11:36,802
[GARBLED NOISES]

154
00:11:36,812 --> 00:11:39,617
GABRIEL:
Oh. Oh, yeah, here we go.

155
00:11:44,120 --> 00:11:45,945
MIKE [ON MONITOR]
Bonner, take this.

156
00:11:45,955 --> 00:11:48,048
Long, toss the ball!

157
00:11:50,226 --> 00:11:51,650
Historical moment.

158
00:11:51,660 --> 00:11:55,287
The first time one of these kids is gonna
get to touch a real American football.

159
00:11:55,297 --> 00:11:56,489
[KIDS CHEERING]

160
00:11:56,499 --> 00:11:59,729
GABRIEL: That's your son?
-That's Mike.

161
00:12:01,270 --> 00:12:06,173
MIKE:
Yeah! No, you're going this way! This way!

162
00:12:07,009 --> 00:12:09,502
Hey, that's my ball, you little fuckers!

163
00:12:09,512 --> 00:12:12,379
Hey! Shit.

164
00:12:12,748 --> 00:12:14,748
-Fuck.
BONNER: A w.

165
00:12:15,117 --> 00:12:16,809
What's wrong, man?

166
00:12:16,819 --> 00:12:20,746
-Did Ali Baba take your football?
MIKE: Turn off the fucking phone.

167
00:12:20,756 --> 00:12:21,947
Any more?

168
00:12:21,957 --> 00:12:25,017
Yeah, but it looks like the rest
of the files are corrupted.

169
00:12:25,027 --> 00:12:28,654
If you want, I have a program at home
that can pull them off.

170
00:12:28,664 --> 00:12:31,824
It's slow, but I could charge you
a hundred flat.

171
00:12:31,834 --> 00:12:35,659
-Can you e-mail them to me?
-Yeah, no problem.

172
00:12:35,905 --> 00:12:38,100
-Thanks.
-Where's TD's?

173
00:12:38,274 --> 00:12:40,936
[HIP-HOP MUSIC PLAYING]

174
00:12:45,614 --> 00:12:47,946
I'm looking for my boy.

175
00:12:52,288 --> 00:12:54,668
[MEN CHEERING AND WHISTLING]

176
00:13:33,028 --> 00:13:35,028
I'm looking for my son.

177
00:13:35,764 --> 00:13:37,389
Good luck.

178
00:13:37,399 --> 00:13:41,130
WAITRESS:
I need four tequila shots! Four!

179
00:14:24,280 --> 00:14:26,405
JOAN [OVER PHONE]:
What are you doing?

180
00:14:26,415 --> 00:14:29,608
Just looking at some old photos
Mike sent me.

181
00:14:29,618 --> 00:14:31,745
You gonna be okay?

182
00:14:34,623 --> 00:14:39,638
It doesn't make sense.
He wouldn't leave without telling us.

183
00:14:39,762 --> 00:14:41,821
I will find him.

184
00:14:42,364 --> 00:14:43,589
[SIGHS]

185
00:14:43,599 --> 00:14:45,599
Okay.

186
00:14:47,136 --> 00:14:48,928
Night.

187
00:14:48,938 --> 00:14:50,938
Good night.

188
00:14:54,843 --> 00:14:56,843
[SIGHS]

189
00:15:22,972 --> 00:15:25,267
HANK:
I can hardly hear you.

190
00:15:25,608 --> 00:15:28,498
MIKE:
You gotta get me out of here.

191
00:15:53,035 --> 00:15:55,840
Well, she should've known better.

192
00:15:56,238 --> 00:15:58,238
Hold a sec.

193
00:16:00,809 --> 00:16:02,735
-Your son is in the Army.
HANK: Yes, ma'am.

194
00:16:02,745 --> 00:16:04,970
Then you need to see the military police.

195
00:16:04,980 --> 00:16:08,240
They're busy with the war.
I'm trying to check things out.

196
00:16:08,250 --> 00:16:10,876
-You can file a missing person's report.
-Fine.

197
00:16:10,886 --> 00:16:15,214
In which case, you'll need to see
the military police.

198
00:16:15,224 --> 00:16:19,985
How about you let me talk to somebody
that does more than answer a phone?

199
00:16:19,995 --> 00:16:21,995
[CHATTERING]

200
00:16:25,534 --> 00:16:30,039
Sir, I wondered if you could
help me with this, um....

201
00:16:30,439 --> 00:16:33,565
WOMAN: I don't think you understand.
He loved that dog.

202
00:16:33,575 --> 00:16:36,435
I'm sure he did, ma'am,
but the dog bit him.

203
00:16:36,445 --> 00:16:39,405
-When a dog bites you, what do you do?
-I really don't know.

204
00:16:39,415 --> 00:16:42,441
You tie it up, you give it away,
you might even shoot it.

205
00:16:42,451 --> 00:16:45,744
You don't pick it up by the throat,
wrestle it into the bathroom...

206
00:16:45,754 --> 00:16:47,446
...and drown it in the tub.

207
00:16:47,456 --> 00:16:48,614
[WAYNE BARKS]

208
00:16:48,624 --> 00:16:50,616
That doesn't sound
a little bit strange to you?

209
00:16:50,626 --> 00:16:52,584
[WAYNE BARKS THEN BOTH LAUGH]

210
00:16:52,594 --> 00:16:54,620
Maybe he thought it was more humane.

211
00:16:54,630 --> 00:16:57,258
More humane? It's a Doberman.

212
00:16:57,433 --> 00:17:00,626
He's drowning it right in front of our son
and it's biting him.

213
00:17:00,636 --> 00:17:05,631
And I'm crying for him to stop.
That all sounds humane to you?

214
00:17:05,641 --> 00:17:07,866
Your husband ever threaten you
or your child?

215
00:17:07,876 --> 00:17:09,935
He'd never hurt us. He just needs help.

216
00:17:09,945 --> 00:17:11,904
That's why you need to go to the VA.

217
00:17:11,914 --> 00:17:14,540
You need to go to them
and ask them about counseling.

218
00:17:14,550 --> 00:17:16,108
You think I haven't
been down there?

219
00:17:16,118 --> 00:17:17,476
[WAYNE BARKS]

220
00:17:17,486 --> 00:17:20,579
He won't go. He's gonna hurt himself.
I know he is.

221
00:17:20,589 --> 00:17:23,248
-Look, I'd really like to help you here.
-Really?

222
00:17:23,258 --> 00:17:26,418
Oh, because it looks to me
like you don't give a crap.

223
00:17:26,428 --> 00:17:28,187
You know, in fact, I do.

224
00:17:28,197 --> 00:17:31,957
But I gotta tell you, crimes against dogs
are particularly hard to prosecute.

225
00:17:31,967 --> 00:17:34,460
If you don't mind,
I have somebody waiting for me.

226
00:17:34,470 --> 00:17:36,850
-Okay. Fuck you, lady.
-Okay.

227
00:17:37,039 --> 00:17:38,664
Great.

228
00:17:38,674 --> 00:17:40,674
[LAUGHING]

229
00:17:45,781 --> 00:17:48,756
HANK:
That kind of morning, huh? Hm.

230
00:17:50,085 --> 00:17:52,211
You gotta take that to military police.

231
00:17:52,221 --> 00:17:56,556
HANK: I'm trying to keep my son
out of more trouble.

232
00:17:56,992 --> 00:17:58,550
I know you're busy...

233
00:17:58,560 --> 00:18:01,854
...but I need you to make one phone call
to his bank and find out...

234
00:18:01,864 --> 00:18:05,224
...if he's made withdrawals or used
his credit card in the last week.

235
00:18:05,234 --> 00:18:07,593
Retired cop, or just watch a lot of TV?

236
00:18:07,603 --> 00:18:09,128
Military police, retired.

237
00:18:09,138 --> 00:18:12,598
Then you should know. Army has
jurisdiction over its own personnel.

238
00:18:12,608 --> 00:18:14,266
Sorry, I hope you find your son.

239
00:18:14,276 --> 00:18:18,137
I don't know what you think your job is,
but if it's anything like mine was...

240
00:18:18,147 --> 00:18:21,874
...it's to roll up drunks, twiddle your
thumbs, not ask too many questions.

241
00:18:21,884 --> 00:18:25,577
But my son has spent the last 1 8 months
bringing democracy to a shithole...

242
00:18:25,587 --> 00:18:27,212
...and serving his country.

243
00:18:27,222 --> 00:18:29,687
He deserves better than this.

244
00:18:38,133 --> 00:18:40,692
PRESIDENT BUSH [ON TV]:
Because we have done the hard work...

245
00:18:40,702 --> 00:18:43,762
...we are entering a season of hope.

246
00:18:45,774 --> 00:18:50,438
My God. Hank Deerfield.
I'll be a son of a bitch.

247
00:18:50,612 --> 00:18:53,772
-What the hell you doing at home?
-Well, you almost missed us.

248
00:18:53,782 --> 00:18:56,208
We're taking the camper
to see the grandkids.

249
00:18:56,218 --> 00:18:58,938
-I called you at the base.
-Base?

250
00:18:59,087 --> 00:19:02,948
Well, Christ, Hank.
I've been retired for 1 4 years.

251
00:19:02,958 --> 00:19:06,121
-You have not.
-Yeah, going on 1 5.

252
00:19:06,295 --> 00:19:08,335
How in the hell are you?

253
00:19:08,430 --> 00:19:11,123
Fine. Oh, want coffee or a piece of pie?

254
00:19:11,133 --> 00:19:15,394
No, no, I don't have time.
Helen's waiting in the camper.

255
00:19:15,404 --> 00:19:16,895
What'd you do...

256
00:19:16,905 --> 00:19:19,631
...bust an axle and call me for a tow?

257
00:19:19,641 --> 00:19:24,336
No, I was hoping you were still at CID.
I'm looking for a friendly face.

258
00:19:24,346 --> 00:19:28,273
-Neither one of your boys in trouble, I hope.
-No.

259
00:19:28,283 --> 00:19:31,443
-What was that oldest one's name, Darren?
-David.

260
00:19:31,453 --> 00:19:34,880
David, that's right.
Joined 82nd Airborne, didn't he?

261
00:19:34,890 --> 00:19:37,482
-Yeah.
-Yeah, tough bunch of sons of bitches.

262
00:19:37,492 --> 00:19:39,517
How's he liking it?

263
00:19:40,429 --> 00:19:45,123
He died in a helicopter crash
on maneuvers at Fort Bragg 1 0 years ago.

264
00:19:45,133 --> 00:19:48,830
Oh, God, I'm sorry to hear that, Hank.

265
00:19:49,004 --> 00:19:51,004
Very sorry.

266
00:19:51,940 --> 00:19:53,832
How about the younger one?

267
00:19:53,842 --> 00:19:55,838
-Mike.
-Yeah.

268
00:19:55,848 --> 00:19:59,872
Regular Army, just like his old man.
In Iraq, doing well.

269
00:19:59,882 --> 00:20:04,443
I'm doing a favor for a neighbor lady.
One of her boys is in a little trouble.

270
00:20:04,453 --> 00:20:07,598
Is there anybody we know still there?

271
00:20:07,723 --> 00:20:09,848
No, no. They're all gone.

272
00:20:11,059 --> 00:20:13,059
[CAR HORN HONKING]

273
00:20:13,528 --> 00:20:16,288
Hmm. She got you on a short leash.

274
00:20:16,298 --> 00:20:17,456
[ARNOLD LAUGHING]

275
00:20:17,466 --> 00:20:19,466
Well, you know.

276
00:20:19,701 --> 00:20:22,033
Kids are waiting for us.

277
00:20:22,971 --> 00:20:24,971
[ARNOLD SIGHS]

278
00:21:04,613 --> 00:21:06,823
I found his old checkbook.

279
00:21:06,949 --> 00:21:11,199
Is there anything written on it?
I need a password.

280
00:21:11,453 --> 00:21:13,663
No, there's nothing on it.

281
00:21:13,822 --> 00:21:15,414
You sure?

282
00:21:15,424 --> 00:21:20,252
Which do you think it is,
I'm blind or I don't feel like telling you?

283
00:21:20,262 --> 00:21:22,120
[SIGHS]

284
00:21:22,130 --> 00:21:24,130
[COMPUTER CHIMES]

285
00:21:29,271 --> 00:21:32,030
I'm worried, Hank. I'm truly worried.

286
00:21:32,040 --> 00:21:35,185
He's a good boy. He'll have a reason.

287
00:21:37,546 --> 00:21:39,271
Hank?

288
00:21:39,281 --> 00:21:42,580
I'll find him. Talk to you tomorrow.

289
00:21:49,658 --> 00:21:52,957
[GARBLED NOISES]

290
00:22:10,612 --> 00:22:12,304
Whoa.

291
00:22:12,314 --> 00:22:13,572
What's going on?

292
00:22:13,582 --> 00:22:17,067
Don't you worry, it's not animal-related.

293
00:22:17,319 --> 00:22:18,643
What?

294
00:22:18,653 --> 00:22:21,513
They found body parts
out on Mesa Luna Road.

295
00:22:21,523 --> 00:22:23,855
-I'll get the car.
-Okay.

296
00:22:24,026 --> 00:22:26,026
[GARBLED NOISES]

297
00:22:28,830 --> 00:22:31,223
MIKE [ON MONITOR]:
Hey, Bonner. There's your family.

298
00:22:31,233 --> 00:22:32,924
[GOAT BLEATING]

299
00:22:32,934 --> 00:22:34,526
Stop fucking around.

300
00:22:34,536 --> 00:22:37,963
MIKE: You could've fucking broken it!
BONNER: You're a fucking idiot.

301
00:22:37,973 --> 00:22:39,264
Oh, fuck.

302
00:22:39,274 --> 00:22:41,133
MIKE:
Oh, shit! What do I do?

303
00:22:41,143 --> 00:22:43,301
BONNER:
Do not stop. Do not fucking stop!

304
00:22:43,311 --> 00:22:45,037
-Speed up! Speed up!
MIKE: Bonner!

305
00:22:45,047 --> 00:22:46,505
[THUDS]

306
00:22:46,515 --> 00:22:48,608
[GARBLED NOISES]

307
00:22:56,691 --> 00:22:59,921
MIKE: Fuck.
BONNER: What are you doing?

308
00:23:06,802 --> 00:23:10,627
MAN:
Maybe go down there a little bit further.

309
00:23:12,174 --> 00:23:15,500
WAYNE:
Aaron, I need more evidence markers.

310
00:23:15,510 --> 00:23:17,637
You got all we have.

311
00:23:17,846 --> 00:23:22,641
Straighten out some wire hangers, and buy
Dixie cups to stick on the ends of them.

312
00:23:22,651 --> 00:23:24,651
Come on.

313
00:23:25,220 --> 00:23:27,220
And get me a receipt.

314
00:23:38,834 --> 00:23:40,834
Sean?

315
00:23:50,745 --> 00:23:52,337
[FLIES BUZZING]

316
00:23:52,347 --> 00:23:54,347
Thanks.

317
00:24:06,128 --> 00:24:08,128
[VEHICLE APPROACHES]

318
00:24:29,818 --> 00:24:32,150
Tell me good news, Hodge.

319
00:24:34,289 --> 00:24:38,817
Well, it looks like the victim
was killed by that fire site there, uh...

320
00:24:38,827 --> 00:24:42,621
...then, uh, the body was chopped up,
it was burned...

321
00:24:42,631 --> 00:24:45,724
...and animals scattered the parts, so....

322
00:24:45,734 --> 00:24:48,460
And you're smiling
like an idiot because...?

323
00:24:48,470 --> 00:24:52,497
Well, the base bought this field
from the city two months ago.

324
00:24:52,507 --> 00:24:57,402
City property only extends 50 feet
from the center line of the road...

325
00:24:57,412 --> 00:25:00,897
...so I don't think it's our body, chief.

326
00:25:02,984 --> 00:25:05,077
Well, hallelujah.

327
00:25:05,253 --> 00:25:07,253
Let's go home.

328
00:25:07,756 --> 00:25:08,980
[WHISTLES]

329
00:25:08,990 --> 00:25:10,315
Wrap it up, fellas!

330
00:25:10,325 --> 00:25:13,817
Boys with the shiny buttons
are coming in.

331
00:25:40,755 --> 00:25:42,755
[HANK SIGHS]

332
00:25:54,669 --> 00:25:55,827
[GRUNTS]

333
00:25:55,837 --> 00:25:57,837
Aah!

334
00:25:58,139 --> 00:26:01,099
REPORTER [ON TV]: It will necessarily
break the back of the insurgency.

335
00:26:01,109 --> 00:26:03,001
MAN [ON TV]:
It is not, though, the panacea.

336
00:26:03,011 --> 00:26:06,538
Just by taking it out does not mean
the rest of the insurgency will fall.

337
00:26:06,548 --> 00:26:09,541
REPORTER: More than half of Fallujah's
250,000 residents...

338
00:26:09,551 --> 00:26:12,577
...have already fled
in anticipation of the offensive.

339
00:26:12,587 --> 00:26:17,015
Insurgents believed to number in the
thousands have been preparing defenses...

340
00:26:17,025 --> 00:26:21,275
...attacking U. S. troops,
and rigging booby traps.

341
00:26:33,275 --> 00:26:35,275
MAN:
Mr. Deerfield?

342
00:26:36,077 --> 00:26:39,877
Jim Osher. Could, uh....
Could I get a word?

343
00:26:40,048 --> 00:26:43,449
Yeah, come on in. I'll just be a minute.

344
00:27:06,007 --> 00:27:08,007
[SIGHS]

345
00:27:20,955 --> 00:27:26,055
Sir, I regret to inform you
that a body was found last night.

346
00:27:26,127 --> 00:27:31,890
Upon investigation, we believe it to be
the remains of your son, Michael Deerfield.

347
00:27:31,900 --> 00:27:35,493
Right. They'll need me
to identify the body?

348
00:27:35,503 --> 00:27:37,395
No, sir. We've--

349
00:27:37,405 --> 00:27:40,999
They've determined identity in other ways.
I believe partial fingerprints.

350
00:27:41,009 --> 00:27:43,668
What do you mean "partial"?
What happened to him?

351
00:27:43,678 --> 00:27:49,458
-I'm not at liberty to say, sir. Someone--
-I wanna see his body now!

352
00:28:13,174 --> 00:28:16,659
Sergeant Deerfield, this isn't necessary.

353
00:28:16,678 --> 00:28:18,770
It's not how you wanna
remember your son.

354
00:28:18,780 --> 00:28:20,780
Maybe not...

355
00:28:20,815 --> 00:28:27,190
...but it's the way he left this earth,
so I don't see as I have any choice.

356
00:28:34,095 --> 00:28:36,654
EXAMINER: Working backwards,
carbon patterns show the body...

357
00:28:36,664 --> 00:28:38,723
...was dismembered
before it was burned.

358
00:28:38,733 --> 00:28:42,293
It appears a large knife or tool
was used, but the blade was dull...

359
00:28:42,303 --> 00:28:45,463
...which is why the bones are
shattered rather than severed.

360
00:28:45,473 --> 00:28:48,366
Burn patterns show us
the dismembered parts were stacked...

361
00:28:48,376 --> 00:28:52,003
...and doused with an accelerant in
an attempt to incinerate the body.

362
00:28:52,013 --> 00:28:55,340
You'd need an oven
to approach an effective temperature...

363
00:28:55,350 --> 00:28:58,176
...which means most tissue
would've been left intact.

364
00:28:58,186 --> 00:29:01,713
So the damage is largely the result
of scavengers stripping the bones.

365
00:29:01,723 --> 00:29:04,315
Cause of death will take
more time to determine...

366
00:29:04,325 --> 00:29:06,518
...but there is evidence of stab wounds.

367
00:29:06,528 --> 00:29:08,353
How many?

368
00:29:08,363 --> 00:29:09,921
I'm sorry?

369
00:29:09,931 --> 00:29:13,658
-How many stab wounds?
-Well, with much of the flesh missing...

370
00:29:13,668 --> 00:29:16,861
...we can only count blows
that made impact with bone.

371
00:29:16,871 --> 00:29:19,336
How many of those were there?

372
00:29:19,741 --> 00:29:21,741
Forty-two.

373
00:29:24,179 --> 00:29:26,204
One knife, or several?

374
00:29:28,283 --> 00:29:30,283
One.

375
00:29:37,592 --> 00:29:41,019
-Gonna turn these over to the Army?
-Tried to.

376
00:29:41,029 --> 00:29:46,894
Said they took their own photos.
And they didn't say it in a nice way.

377
00:29:51,139 --> 00:29:54,065
I'd like to give you
a call tomorrow before you go home.

378
00:29:54,075 --> 00:29:55,800
I have a few questions.

379
00:29:55,810 --> 00:29:57,769
HANK:
Ask them now.

380
00:29:57,779 --> 00:30:01,039
-Your son didn't own a green car?
-Mike doesn't own a car.

381
00:30:01,049 --> 00:30:05,143
Motorist reported seeing a green sedan
parked on the shoulder near the field...

382
00:30:05,153 --> 00:30:06,945
...that Saturday night.

383
00:30:06,955 --> 00:30:11,149
One of the theories is that this is
a carjacking or a robbery gone wrong...

384
00:30:11,159 --> 00:30:14,118
...and there's a big uptick
in gang activity lately.

385
00:30:14,128 --> 00:30:16,338
I wanna see where he died.

386
00:30:16,764 --> 00:30:20,024
I'm sorry. It's an active crime scene,
but I will let you know...

387
00:30:20,034 --> 00:30:22,499
-...as soon as you can.
-Okay.

388
00:30:24,305 --> 00:30:26,500
What else you wanna ask?

389
00:30:28,109 --> 00:30:30,869
A lot of the deaths like these
have been drug-related.

390
00:30:30,879 --> 00:30:34,339
Are you asking if Mike was
a drug dealer or just an addict?

391
00:30:34,349 --> 00:30:36,040
I don't wanna be asking anything.

392
00:30:36,050 --> 00:30:39,310
You know the Army
does regular drug tests.

393
00:30:39,320 --> 00:30:41,445
Not when they're in Iraq.

394
00:30:43,858 --> 00:30:47,118
Now, we found this
under your son's mattress.

395
00:30:47,128 --> 00:30:49,320
It's not gonna go in my report.

396
00:30:49,330 --> 00:30:51,823
But why I ask is last month...

397
00:30:51,833 --> 00:30:56,094
...we arrested three soldiers who were
trying to smuggle heroin in from Kuwait.

398
00:30:56,104 --> 00:30:59,697
They'd made arrangements to sell it
to a local Mexican gang.

399
00:30:59,707 --> 00:31:01,966
I understand Mike spoke a little Spanish?

400
00:31:01,976 --> 00:31:06,004
And you think he could've been a drug mule
because he spoke Spanish?

401
00:31:06,014 --> 00:31:07,772
No...

402
00:31:07,782 --> 00:31:12,032
...because somebody cut off
his hands and his head.

403
00:31:52,760 --> 00:31:55,490
I'm really sorry about your son.

404
00:31:58,333 --> 00:32:00,333
Show me.

405
00:32:02,503 --> 00:32:04,503
I'm sorry?

406
00:32:06,674 --> 00:32:09,054
I need to see where he died.

407
00:32:09,510 --> 00:32:11,603
It's not our case.

408
00:32:12,013 --> 00:32:14,072
The murder occurred on military property.

409
00:32:14,082 --> 00:32:16,507
-You know where it is?
-There's nothing to see.

410
00:32:16,517 --> 00:32:21,022
Then there shouldn't be any problem
with me seeing it.

411
00:32:21,189 --> 00:32:23,189
[SANDERS SIGHS]

412
00:32:28,429 --> 00:32:35,484
HANK: You people sure as hell know how to
trample a crime scene, I'll give you that.

413
00:32:42,543 --> 00:32:44,469
I suppose you thought
it was a good idea...

414
00:32:44,479 --> 00:32:49,154
...to have everybody you ever met
park on this shoulder.

415
00:32:52,654 --> 00:32:54,712
If your boys knew
what they were doing...

416
00:32:54,722 --> 00:32:58,549
...they'd have found traces of blood
in the gravel right here.

417
00:32:58,559 --> 00:33:00,652
It's where he was killed.

418
00:33:00,662 --> 00:33:03,321
So you don't see blood,
but you know it's there?

419
00:33:03,331 --> 00:33:04,922
Yeah.

420
00:33:04,932 --> 00:33:09,095
Just like I know his body
was dragged from here...

421
00:33:09,105 --> 00:33:10,995
...to there.

422
00:33:11,005 --> 00:33:13,064
That's remarkable.

423
00:33:13,408 --> 00:33:16,434
The ground is rock-hard,
but you see drag marks.

424
00:33:16,444 --> 00:33:22,106
You go to the trouble to burn a body,
don't you think you'd cover your tracks?

425
00:33:22,116 --> 00:33:24,326
I'm going to the restroom.

426
00:33:29,457 --> 00:33:32,216
You might find it easier
to drive around that field.

427
00:33:32,226 --> 00:33:34,946
You couldn't do any more damage.

428
00:33:41,836 --> 00:33:44,811
SANDERS:
Everybody knows everything.

429
00:33:45,506 --> 00:33:48,805
[COUNTRY MUSIC PLAYING ON RADIO]

430
00:33:59,153 --> 00:34:01,112
WOMAN: Hi.
-Hi.

431
00:34:01,122 --> 00:34:03,915
-Can I help you?
-I suppose the MPs have been in here...

432
00:34:03,925 --> 00:34:07,018
...asking questions about
what happened in that field.

433
00:34:07,028 --> 00:34:11,189
-They sure have. Terrible thing.
-I'm checking it out for the family.

434
00:34:11,199 --> 00:34:13,257
Mind if I ask if you saw anything?

435
00:34:13,267 --> 00:34:15,560
I wish we had.
We would've liked to help.

436
00:34:15,570 --> 00:34:18,396
We didn't know what it was
when we smelled it, did we?

437
00:34:18,406 --> 00:34:20,406
MAN: No.
-How's that?

438
00:34:20,475 --> 00:34:23,034
That Sunday,
when we drove in the parking lot...

439
00:34:23,044 --> 00:34:25,870
...we just thought somebody
had been barbecuing.

440
00:34:25,880 --> 00:34:28,849
Smelled like, um, burned meat.

441
00:34:31,252 --> 00:34:33,252
Thank you.

442
00:35:22,103 --> 00:35:25,863
HANK: Tell your MP friends they should be
looking for a blue car, not a green one.

443
00:35:25,873 --> 00:35:27,064
Why?

444
00:35:27,074 --> 00:35:30,968
Because a blue car under
a yellow light looks green.

445
00:35:30,978 --> 00:35:32,978
Doesn't it?

446
00:35:46,327 --> 00:35:48,327
It certainly does.

447
00:35:57,171 --> 00:35:59,171
Thank you.

448
00:35:59,240 --> 00:36:01,470
It's the least I could do.

449
00:36:02,510 --> 00:36:04,671
I'd say that's accurate.

450
00:36:18,693 --> 00:36:21,352
JOAN [OVER PHONE]:
I'll get a plane ticket.

451
00:36:21,362 --> 00:36:23,362
No.

452
00:36:24,332 --> 00:36:26,257
What do you mean, "No"?

453
00:36:26,267 --> 00:36:29,157
I'll bring him home soon as I can.

454
00:36:29,203 --> 00:36:33,299
I need to see him.
I need to be with Michael.

455
00:36:33,608 --> 00:36:35,604
He's gone.

456
00:36:35,614 --> 00:36:37,735
I need to be with my boy.

457
00:36:38,346 --> 00:36:40,974
There is nothing left.

458
00:36:43,484 --> 00:36:46,112
What the hell does that mean?

459
00:36:47,688 --> 00:36:51,115
Joanie, for once in your life,
will you take my word for something?

460
00:36:51,125 --> 00:36:53,753
For once? For once?

461
00:36:53,928 --> 00:36:56,554
I seem to remember
me being the one saying no...

462
00:36:56,564 --> 00:37:00,391
...and you saying it'd be good for his
character. Who won that argument, Hank?

463
00:37:00,401 --> 00:37:04,061
Mike was the one who wanted to join.
I sure as hell didn't encourage it.

464
00:37:04,071 --> 00:37:08,666
Living in this house, he never could've
felt like a man if he hadn't gone.

465
00:37:08,676 --> 00:37:10,501
[JOAN SOBS]

466
00:37:10,511 --> 00:37:14,506
Both of my boys, Hank.
You could've left me one.

467
00:37:16,684 --> 00:37:18,879
[JOAN SOBBING]

468
00:37:26,594 --> 00:37:28,594
Joanie?

469
00:37:32,066 --> 00:37:34,364
Joan, please.

470
00:37:43,945 --> 00:37:47,855
Joanie, I can't sit here
and listen to you cry.

471
00:37:51,352 --> 00:37:53,377
Well, then don't.

472
00:38:49,810 --> 00:38:51,810
DAVID:
Door.

473
00:38:54,749 --> 00:38:56,749
Night.

474
00:38:57,451 --> 00:38:59,451
Night, sweetheart.

475
00:39:29,150 --> 00:39:30,975
SOLDIER [ON MONITOR]:
Oh, fuck!

476
00:39:30,985 --> 00:39:32,576
[GARBLED NOISES]

477
00:39:32,586 --> 00:39:34,645
[GUNFIRE]
[EXPLOSIONS]

478
00:39:37,158 --> 00:39:39,050
BONNER:
Another hallway left. Stacked, on me.

479
00:39:39,060 --> 00:39:40,851
Ortiez, cover this door to the right.

480
00:39:40,861 --> 00:39:43,454
To the right.
Penning, get this door with me. Long!

481
00:39:43,464 --> 00:39:45,122
PENNING: Roger!
LONG: Covering!

482
00:39:45,132 --> 00:39:46,957
PENNING:
Got it.

483
00:39:46,967 --> 00:39:48,392
BONNER:
Go, go.

484
00:39:48,402 --> 00:39:50,893
-Clear. Clear.
SOLDIER: Clear.

485
00:39:51,739 --> 00:39:55,666
BONNER: Give me a status on that door!
Better not fuck around with that phone!

486
00:39:55,676 --> 00:39:58,056
MIKE:
Absolutely not, Bonner!

487
00:39:58,646 --> 00:40:01,451
See how the clothes aren't burnt?

488
00:40:04,385 --> 00:40:06,649
It's really weird, Dad.

489
00:40:07,555 --> 00:40:12,995
BONNER: Right, all clear. Let's move it out!
ORTIEZ: Move it out.

490
00:40:26,340 --> 00:40:28,900
[ROCK MUSIC PLAYING]

491
00:40:31,846 --> 00:40:33,037
BARTENDER:
Sure.

492
00:40:33,047 --> 00:40:35,277
Evie, chicken sandwich.

493
00:40:50,965 --> 00:40:52,965
[PEOPLE CHEERING ON TV]

494
00:41:02,810 --> 00:41:05,190
-Mustard or mayonnaise?
-Um--

495
00:41:06,046 --> 00:41:08,046
No, thank you, ma'am.

496
00:41:08,082 --> 00:41:11,142
EVIE: A woman stands topless
in front of you...

497
00:41:11,152 --> 00:41:14,467
..."ma'am" could be taken as an insult.

498
00:41:15,589 --> 00:41:17,548
-Hmm, this your son?
-Yes, ma'am.

499
00:41:17,558 --> 00:41:21,652
I'm asking if anybody saw him.
It would've been a week ago Saturday.

500
00:41:21,662 --> 00:41:26,167
I'm sorry. I don't recognize
anything but the uniform.

501
00:41:27,902 --> 00:41:30,234
Thank you, ma'am. Miss.

502
00:41:34,341 --> 00:41:36,341
[MAN CHUCKLES]

503
00:41:38,679 --> 00:41:40,679
OFFICER:
Right here.

504
00:41:47,454 --> 00:41:49,945
[WAYNE CLUCKING]

505
00:41:59,466 --> 00:42:01,466
SANDERS:
Stay here.

506
00:42:01,869 --> 00:42:03,869
Excuse me, lieutenant?

507
00:42:03,938 --> 00:42:06,797
I was just wondering how
I came to be assigned this case.

508
00:42:06,807 --> 00:42:08,465
Uh, which case?

509
00:42:08,475 --> 00:42:10,201
Jacob Ronald Millard...

510
00:42:10,211 --> 00:42:13,704
...slaughterhouse employee,
arrested for torturing chickens.

511
00:42:13,714 --> 00:42:15,973
It's no big deal. Everybody does it.

512
00:42:15,983 --> 00:42:18,275
Everybody doesn't poke
their eyes out, asshole.

513
00:42:18,285 --> 00:42:20,244
-Sure, they do.
-Shut up!

514
00:42:20,254 --> 00:42:23,547
Boss doesn't want me
humping his daughter.

515
00:42:23,557 --> 00:42:25,916
Now we're shocked beyond words.

516
00:42:25,926 --> 00:42:28,819
You see how you could draw
information out of people?

517
00:42:28,829 --> 00:42:31,229
People just like you, Emily.

518
00:42:31,398 --> 00:42:36,160
That is how you got promoted from
traffic to detective squad, am I right?

519
00:42:36,170 --> 00:42:37,595
I'm sorry?

520
00:42:37,605 --> 00:42:39,800
BURKE:
Oh, don't be.

521
00:42:39,974 --> 00:42:43,901
If Wayne or Hodge could've fucked their
way into the squad, they would've too.

522
00:42:43,911 --> 00:42:45,402
Well, Wayne would have.

523
00:42:45,412 --> 00:42:47,471
One of us needs to know
what we're doing.

524
00:42:47,481 --> 00:42:49,206
[LAUGHING]

525
00:42:49,216 --> 00:42:52,977
You see, that's what concerns me.
Having fucked my way into the job...

526
00:42:52,987 --> 00:42:57,748
...I may not be qualified enough to piece
together this complex of a crime.

527
00:42:57,758 --> 00:42:59,416
I mean, take that murder site.

528
00:42:59,426 --> 00:43:03,454
I would've never concluded that
that soldier was killed on Army property.

529
00:43:03,464 --> 00:43:07,091
I would've been fooled by the signs
of struggle on the side of the road.

530
00:43:07,101 --> 00:43:11,195
And you know that little trail of broken
brush from there to where he was burned?

531
00:43:11,205 --> 00:43:16,300
Well, that would've made me think he was
killed in our jurisdiction, and then moved.

532
00:43:16,310 --> 00:43:20,337
Because the killers didn't think it smart
to chop him up under a bright streetlight.

533
00:43:20,347 --> 00:43:24,512
Yeah. I would've totally
misread that crime scene.

534
00:43:30,724 --> 00:43:33,417
BUCHWALD:
No, no, no. It's good work.

535
00:43:33,427 --> 00:43:35,853
I mean, we needed another homicide.

536
00:43:35,863 --> 00:43:39,390
What, we've solved three
out of the last 1 0?

537
00:43:39,400 --> 00:43:42,226
Another unsolved would cement
my standing with the mayor.

538
00:43:42,236 --> 00:43:44,595
You have a problem with
your fellow detectives?

539
00:43:44,605 --> 00:43:47,164
-You feel the need to show them up?
-No, sir.

540
00:43:47,174 --> 00:43:49,400
So it's the military police?

541
00:43:49,410 --> 00:43:52,369
You think they're boobs,
they'll bungle the investigation?

542
00:43:52,379 --> 00:43:56,674
No, but let's not pretend we don't know the
real motives for the Army wanting this case.

543
00:43:56,684 --> 00:44:00,978
Psychic powers.
When did you discover you had these?

544
00:44:00,988 --> 00:44:05,249
You don't believe their primary concern will
be how this incident reflects on the Army?

545
00:44:05,259 --> 00:44:07,251
This is a career move? Is that it?

546
00:44:07,261 --> 00:44:09,787
I don't have a career, sir. I have a job.

547
00:44:09,797 --> 00:44:11,989
I take care of my son
and do what I'm told.

548
00:44:11,999 --> 00:44:14,658
This boy died in a ditch
beside one of our streets.

549
00:44:14,668 --> 00:44:18,996
Someone burned him like a cord of wood,
leaving his remains for animals to chew on.

550
00:44:19,006 --> 00:44:21,799
With respect, if that was your son
just back from Iraq...

551
00:44:21,809 --> 00:44:25,002
...I don't think you'd be as happy
about tossing this case off...

552
00:44:25,012 --> 00:44:27,871
...so you look better come election time.

553
00:44:27,881 --> 00:44:31,208
-That was with respect?
-That was my intent, sir.

554
00:44:31,218 --> 00:44:33,777
Fine. I'll think about it
and I'll let you know.

555
00:44:33,787 --> 00:44:35,713
Every second we lose in this--

556
00:44:35,723 --> 00:44:38,649
Didn't you say that you would do
whatever you were told?

557
00:44:38,659 --> 00:44:42,229
-I sometimes exaggerate for effect.
-Mm-hm.

558
00:44:45,899 --> 00:44:47,899
How's David?

559
00:44:48,035 --> 00:44:49,360
Sorry?

560
00:44:49,370 --> 00:44:51,370
Your son.

561
00:44:52,940 --> 00:44:54,598
He's fine, thanks for asking.

562
00:44:54,608 --> 00:44:58,302
That, uh, deadbeat ex of yours ever
show up for any of his games?

563
00:44:58,312 --> 00:45:00,904
David's pretty pathetic
at every sport he attempts...

564
00:45:00,914 --> 00:45:03,674
...so he wants as few people
to witness it as possible.

565
00:45:03,684 --> 00:45:06,377
Well, that's a damn shame, isn't it?

566
00:45:06,387 --> 00:45:09,447
It's not like he's the boy's father.

567
00:45:10,791 --> 00:45:12,791
[BUCHWALD SIGHS]

568
00:45:12,993 --> 00:45:14,993
Anyway, way I see it...

569
00:45:15,129 --> 00:45:19,456
...it's the oddballs and the misfits who go
on to do interesting things with their lives.

570
00:45:19,466 --> 00:45:21,792
How many former
high school quarterbacks...

571
00:45:21,802 --> 00:45:25,062
...do we roll into the drunk tank
every Saturday night?

572
00:45:25,072 --> 00:45:27,664
Little misery in school is a good thing.

573
00:45:27,674 --> 00:45:32,102
You know, I was first-string quarterback
in my high school.

574
00:45:32,112 --> 00:45:35,873
I seem to recall you
showing me pictures of such, sir.

575
00:45:35,883 --> 00:45:37,883
Mm.

576
00:45:42,322 --> 00:45:45,549
You're gonna keep after me
about this Deerfield boy, aren't you?

577
00:45:45,559 --> 00:45:49,319
I think you know what
the right thing to do is, sir.

578
00:45:49,329 --> 00:45:51,329
Hmm.

579
00:45:51,865 --> 00:45:54,356
Jesus H. Christ.

580
00:45:56,270 --> 00:45:57,728
-Hilary.
WOMAN: Yes, sir?

581
00:45:57,738 --> 00:46:01,818
-Get me Captain Fenderman at the base.
-Yes, sir.

582
00:46:15,522 --> 00:46:18,582
[WOMAN SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY
OVER PA]

583
00:46:44,084 --> 00:46:47,909
KIRKLANDER:
Would you like to sit down, ma'am?

584
00:46:49,990 --> 00:46:51,990
Is that everything?

585
00:46:53,727 --> 00:46:55,727
Is that all of him?

586
00:46:55,829 --> 00:46:57,829
KIRKLANDER:
Yes, ma'am.

587
00:46:59,333 --> 00:47:02,826
-You must have to keep that room cold.
KIRKLANDER: Yes, ma'am.

588
00:47:02,836 --> 00:47:04,861
That looks cold.

589
00:47:09,343 --> 00:47:13,006
I wanna go inside. Can I go inside?

590
00:47:16,383 --> 00:47:18,613
No, ma'am. I'm sorry.

591
00:47:30,330 --> 00:47:32,795
My deepest sympathies, ma'am.

592
00:47:36,270 --> 00:47:39,137
You don't have a child, do you?

593
00:47:40,941 --> 00:47:42,941
Do you?

594
00:49:06,960 --> 00:49:08,960
[KNOCKING]

595
00:49:12,799 --> 00:49:14,799
-Mr. Deerfield?
-Hi.

596
00:49:14,968 --> 00:49:17,527
I heard you ask if you
could have Mike's Bible...

597
00:49:17,537 --> 00:49:20,030
...and I thought it might
bring you some comfort.

598
00:49:20,040 --> 00:49:21,698
Anybody know you took this?

599
00:49:21,708 --> 00:49:26,970
No, sir. I asked the visitors' center
where you were staying and they told me.

600
00:49:26,980 --> 00:49:28,705
Can I buy you a coffee?

601
00:49:28,715 --> 00:49:30,840
I really should get back.

602
00:49:32,686 --> 00:49:34,686
How about a drink?

603
00:50:15,062 --> 00:50:17,062
To Mike.

604
00:50:24,871 --> 00:50:29,467
I need to ask you something.
And I want the truth.

605
00:50:31,912 --> 00:50:33,770
Was Mike doing drugs?

606
00:50:33,780 --> 00:50:36,874
Doc? I guess.

607
00:50:37,584 --> 00:50:42,713
No more than the other guys.
He wasn't like a heavy doper or anything.

608
00:50:42,723 --> 00:50:46,650
You ever see him hanging out
off the base with anyone?

609
00:50:46,660 --> 00:50:48,552
Maybe Mexicans?

610
00:50:48,562 --> 00:50:50,562
No, sir.

611
00:50:53,300 --> 00:50:55,300
How you adjusting?

612
00:50:55,402 --> 00:50:57,563
-Being back?
-Mm.

613
00:50:58,472 --> 00:51:00,472
Hasn't been that long.

614
00:51:00,774 --> 00:51:02,666
Call your parents?

615
00:51:02,676 --> 00:51:06,009
My mom. My dad and I aren't close.

616
00:51:08,782 --> 00:51:11,649
-Did you guys talk much?
-Sure.

617
00:51:13,653 --> 00:51:15,917
We could've talked more.

618
00:51:20,293 --> 00:51:22,986
Did he ever say anything to you
that I should know?

619
00:51:22,996 --> 00:51:24,996
No, sir.

620
00:51:25,198 --> 00:51:27,198
I mean...

621
00:51:27,367 --> 00:51:30,127
...you see shit over there
you don't wanna talk about...

622
00:51:30,137 --> 00:51:32,195
-...even with your buddies.
-Yeah.

623
00:51:32,205 --> 00:51:34,164
But he did all right, Mike?

624
00:51:34,174 --> 00:51:36,639
He was a first-class soldier.

625
00:51:37,344 --> 00:51:40,149
You know Mike. He loved the Army.

626
00:51:40,347 --> 00:51:46,127
Couldn't wait to get there, save
the good guys and hurt the bad guys.

627
00:51:50,524 --> 00:51:54,434
They shouldn't send heroes
to places like Iraq.

628
00:51:54,961 --> 00:51:57,426
Everything there's fucked up.

629
00:51:58,465 --> 00:52:03,198
Before I went, I'd never say this,
but you ask me now...

630
00:52:05,138 --> 00:52:10,408
...they should just nuke it
and watch it all turn back to dust.

631
00:52:14,681 --> 00:52:16,681
JOAN:
Hank?

632
00:52:17,083 --> 00:52:18,909
You okay?

633
00:52:18,919 --> 00:52:22,245
HANK:
Yeah, I was just about to call you.

634
00:52:22,255 --> 00:52:24,635
A package came from Michael.

635
00:52:28,061 --> 00:52:30,020
What kind of package?

636
00:52:30,030 --> 00:52:34,691
I don't know, it's a package.
He sent it to himself. It's from overseas.

637
00:52:34,701 --> 00:52:36,126
I'm gonna open it.

638
00:52:36,136 --> 00:52:37,427
No.

639
00:52:37,437 --> 00:52:39,496
What do you mean, "No"?

640
00:52:40,373 --> 00:52:44,668
Does it look like it's been opened
by customs or by the military?

641
00:52:44,678 --> 00:52:48,273
How would I know? No, it doesn't.

642
00:52:48,448 --> 00:52:49,773
Why can't I open it?

643
00:52:49,783 --> 00:52:51,408
Just don't.

644
00:52:51,418 --> 00:52:53,418
Please. Um....

645
00:52:54,387 --> 00:52:56,719
Just put it someplace safe.

646
00:52:59,426 --> 00:53:01,426
Okay.

647
00:53:02,696 --> 00:53:05,028
-Night.
-Good night.

648
00:54:02,622 --> 00:54:04,681
-Morning.
-Morning.

649
00:54:05,091 --> 00:54:07,984
I wonder if I could ask you
a few questions about your son.

650
00:54:07,994 --> 00:54:10,987
-I thought it wasn't your case.
-It sort of fell back to me.

651
00:54:10,997 --> 00:54:13,377
Isn't that our good fortune?

652
00:54:14,000 --> 00:54:16,760
I was wondering if you knew
if your son had any enemies.

653
00:54:16,770 --> 00:54:20,463
You mean other than the thousands
of Iraqis and foreign fighters...

654
00:54:20,473 --> 00:54:22,899
...trying to kill him
till a couple of weeks ago?

655
00:54:22,909 --> 00:54:26,564
Yeah, that shirt looks like it's still wet.

656
00:54:26,947 --> 00:54:28,947
It's dry enough.

657
00:54:28,982 --> 00:54:31,608
Anything bothering him
that you know about?

658
00:54:31,618 --> 00:54:33,176
No.

659
00:54:33,186 --> 00:54:35,712
You looking into the gang connection?

660
00:54:35,722 --> 00:54:39,649
Why? You have reason to think your son
was involved in gangs or drugs?

661
00:54:39,659 --> 00:54:41,659
No.

662
00:54:42,228 --> 00:54:44,854
-When did you last speak to him?
-Why?

663
00:54:44,864 --> 00:54:48,692
Capital One faxed me a recent summary
of his credit-card charges.

664
00:54:48,702 --> 00:54:50,794
After he got back,
he bought tube socks--

665
00:54:50,804 --> 00:54:53,530
I told him a dozen times,
those are the worst socks.

666
00:54:53,540 --> 00:54:56,866
They have no heel,
they wear right through.

667
00:54:56,876 --> 00:55:00,170
--and then he went out for some chicken.

668
00:55:00,180 --> 00:55:02,005
Does it say what time?

669
00:55:02,015 --> 00:55:04,015
And no more charges.

670
00:55:04,851 --> 00:55:09,212
We assume your son was killed sometime
Saturday night or Sunday morning.

671
00:55:09,222 --> 00:55:11,815
We haven't found his wallet,
but if it was stolen...

672
00:55:11,825 --> 00:55:16,653
...we'd see a lot more charges on it,
like computers, stereos, what have you.

673
00:55:16,663 --> 00:55:19,978
Have you been to the chicken place yet?

674
00:55:25,672 --> 00:55:28,140
[LATIN MUSIC PLAYING]

675
00:55:35,815 --> 00:55:39,012
MAN: Enjoy.
-How can I help you?

676
00:55:39,185 --> 00:55:41,945
We're inquiring about a soldier
who was here a week ago.

677
00:55:41,955 --> 00:55:44,714
You're kidding me, right?
We're a block from the base.

678
00:55:44,724 --> 00:55:46,783
Can you tell what time he was here?

679
00:55:46,793 --> 00:55:49,091
It's the last four digits.

680
00:55:49,262 --> 00:55:54,257
1:03 a.m. Sunday morning.
We bill that as Saturday. Anything else?

681
00:55:54,267 --> 00:55:58,094
-Can you tell us what he bought?
-Not without the actual receipt.

682
00:55:58,104 --> 00:56:00,104
Okay. Thank you.

683
00:56:00,240 --> 00:56:04,134
Your four-piece dinner is $6.79.
Is that what most people order?

684
00:56:04,144 --> 00:56:05,735
That or the three-piece.

685
00:56:05,745 --> 00:56:07,745
So with tax...

686
00:56:07,881 --> 00:56:11,612
...$21.77 would be...

687
00:56:11,785 --> 00:56:13,877
...three meals, three people.

688
00:56:13,887 --> 00:56:18,902
Four, if it's the three-piece,
or one really hungry soldier.

689
00:56:46,920 --> 00:56:49,813
There you are.
I just dropped something off for you.

690
00:56:49,823 --> 00:56:52,582
-You did?
-We took statements from Mike's squad.

691
00:56:52,592 --> 00:56:54,050
Thought you'd want them.

692
00:56:54,060 --> 00:56:57,020
That's great. I was gonna call you
to arrange interviews.

693
00:56:57,030 --> 00:56:59,030
Saved you the trouble.

694
00:56:59,632 --> 00:57:01,524
How so?

695
00:57:01,534 --> 00:57:04,084
Sworn statements on your desk.

696
00:57:04,304 --> 00:57:07,964
What, you didn't think
I'd want to interview them myself?

697
00:57:07,974 --> 00:57:10,633
Just trying to give you a leg up.

698
00:57:10,643 --> 00:57:13,403
Thanks. I sort of like to do
my own detective work.

699
00:57:13,413 --> 00:57:15,413
I'll tell you what.

700
00:57:15,482 --> 00:57:16,940
Read the statements.

701
00:57:16,950 --> 00:57:21,811
If you still wanna question them,
I will be glad to take the request to my C.O.

702
00:57:21,821 --> 00:57:23,580
Perhaps you misunderstood me.

703
00:57:23,590 --> 00:57:26,716
It's not a request.
I want the list of the men in his unit.

704
00:57:26,726 --> 00:57:29,619
-On your desk.
-And I wanna interview them this afternoon.

705
00:57:29,629 --> 00:57:31,821
You'll have to go to my C.O.
with that one.

706
00:57:31,831 --> 00:57:35,825
-My chief already spoke to him.
-This one's a bit of a jurisdictional mess.

707
00:57:35,835 --> 00:57:39,529
There is no mess. The murder was
committed in our jurisdiction.

708
00:57:39,539 --> 00:57:42,832
That's where it gets murky. Read those.

709
00:57:42,842 --> 00:57:45,732
I'd be glad to put the request in.

710
00:57:51,684 --> 00:57:55,145
-You don't have the sworn statements?
-I have the statements--

711
00:57:55,155 --> 00:57:57,614
Then they're cooperating.
I don't see the problem.

712
00:57:57,624 --> 00:57:59,983
I have a right to interview
potential witnesses.

713
00:57:59,993 --> 00:58:03,753
-Has the Army said you can't?
-They said they'd consider my request.

714
00:58:03,763 --> 00:58:05,321
And that was 1 0 minutes ago.

715
00:58:05,331 --> 00:58:08,691
And I'd like to talk to these men
before they've been coached...

716
00:58:08,701 --> 00:58:12,695
...or debriefed so any inconsistencies
in their stories will have disappeared.

717
00:58:12,705 --> 00:58:15,565
Being a former military man,
I'm sure you've seen that...

718
00:58:15,575 --> 00:58:20,080
...perhaps when you served
with Lieutenant Kirklander?

719
00:58:20,847 --> 00:58:22,972
I'll tell you what. Ahem.

720
00:58:23,116 --> 00:58:26,516
Skip upstairs and cry to your boyfriend.

721
00:58:26,886 --> 00:58:30,881
Because I'm just not in the mood
to give a shit.

722
00:59:13,032 --> 00:59:17,594
REPORTER [ON TV]: We're showing video
that has just come in to CNN from Fallujah.

723
00:59:17,604 --> 00:59:19,604
You ordered yet?

724
00:59:26,946 --> 00:59:29,156
SANDERS:
Okay. Dig in, men.

725
00:59:47,533 --> 00:59:49,763
-May I?
SANDERS: Please.

726
00:59:52,405 --> 00:59:55,465
SANDERS: Okay. Out.
-No, I can do it.

